content.description:
Scramble up to the grassy ledge where the first pro can be found. Good pro through lower crux off ledge, with adequate placements through easier terrain above. Upper crux is bolt protected and has some great climbing (don't get suckered to the left). The top anchor is set back from the top so if leading it is advisable to pre-set the anchor on the way down to the base of the crag.

The top anchor is located beyond the railing about 30ft right (NW) of the corner (looking out) on top of a small prow. There is an obvious trail that continues around to the base of the crag. The route takes the direct line from base to prow
Trad gear and bolts. Two-bolt anchor (hangars, not rings)

Follow the flake through good stances, then make a tricky move or two up the face and to the right to reach the anchor.


Second climb you come to once you reach the base of the crag. The anchor is on the top of the cliff (as opposed to the face) to facilitate TR set-up.

6 bolts plus two-bolt anchor

Starts with a few slabby moves, up & over a small prow and then up to the anchors



In between Beothuk Arrow(on the left) & closest to Overbite(on the right)

Bolts to two bolt anchor with rap hangers (not accessible from top

Nice easy face climbing


Bolts with metal biners on anchor bolts

Tricky slab climbing up to a small roof. Clip a high bolt from below the roof, then move right for a powerful layback sequence up through it. Easier climbing above


Hangers at top. Access from the top can be protected by utilizing the railing.

Start just right of boltine on good jugs, traverse left under the boltline and start heading up. Feet are a bit tricky to find, but are there. Crux is between bolts 1 and 2 and can be done a variety of ways- just have an attentive belayer to keep you off the ground as a fall could be dangerous. Once at bolt 2 the climbing eases up as you romp to the top. You can set up a TR on your way down or lead the climb. I'd recommend topping first if you aren't comfortable leading .10s 



The leftmost route at James Cook Lookout- left of Jekyll and Hyde

4 bolt to anchors

Somewhat tricky holds down low lead to positive edges, jugs, and an awesome under cling up high.

Second route on the wall, directly left of Jekyll and Hyde
5 bolts, plus anchor w/ rappel rings

Nice easy slab climbing, most difficult moves at the bottom and then ledges to the top. Great first lead!



Starts up obvious slabby arete about 40m to the right of "Overbite"

Bolts with anchors at top of cliff. Requires pre-set anchor.

Starting with some tricky moves for the grade and trending to the right through an easier section with good rest before the vertical crux, with good holds, to the top. The anchors are hangers over top of cliff and it is recommended to be lead with pre-build TR anchor, although topping out is possible 

The third bolted route from the left of the crag.
9 bolts with anchor bolts at top of cliff. Quad or other anchor needed.

Cook's Lookout AKA Captain James Cook National Historic Site is right in town, with great views of the city and the Bay of Islands. Don't be surprised by startled tourist when you top out! 
 This crag is very beginner friendly and has mostly moderate routes with easy TR access 
  
 It seems a lot of people toss garbage from the lookout, so feel free to bring a small bag to help keep the crag clean.
